      "FacilityID": 1000096682,
      "SummaryText": "Executive Summary\n\nThe stationary source and regulated substances handled: \n\nSynthomer Jefferson Hills LLC (\"Synthomer\") produces hydrocarbon resins from organic feedstocks which are used in a variety of adhesive applications.  RMP-regulated substances handled on site are 1,3-Pentadiene, 2-Methylpropene, Hydrogen, Boron Trifluoride, and Anhydrous Ammonia.\n\nThe accidental release prevention and emergency response policies at the stationary source:\n\nSynthomer is a member of the American Chemistry Council and subscribes to the principles of Responsible Care.  Our accidental release prevention and emergency response polices are found in the Responsible Care Pledge which reads in part:\nWe pledge:\n\u00bf\tTo lead our Company in ethical ways that increasingly benefit society, the economy and the environment.\n\u00bf\tTo design and develop products that can be manufactured, transported, used and disposed of or recycled safely.\n\u00bf\tTo work with customers, carriers, suppliers, distributors and contractors to foster the safe and secure use, transport and disposal of chemicals and provide hazard and risk information that can be accessed and applied in their operations and products.\n\u00bf\tTo design and operate our facilities in a safe, secure and environmentally sound manner.\n\u00bf\tTo instill a culture throughout all levels of our organization to continually identify, reduce and manage process safety risks.\n\u00bf\tTo promote pollution prevention, minimization of waste and conservation of energy and other critical resources at every stage of the life cycle of our products.\n\u00bf\tTo cooperate with governments at all levels and organizations in the development of effective and efficient safety, health, environmental and security laws, regulations and standards.\n\u00bf\tTo support education and research on the health, safety, environmental effects and security of our products and processes.\n\u00bf\tTo communicate product, service and process risks to our stakeholders and listen to and consider their perspectives.\n\u00bf\tTo make co"
    },
    {
      "ESSeqNum": 1,
      "FacilityID": 1000096682,
      "SummaryText": "ntinual progress toward our goal of no accidents, injuries or harm to human health and the environment from our products and operations and to be transparent in reporting our health, safety, environmental and security performance.\n\u00bf\tTo seek continual improvement in our integrated Responsible Care Management System; to address environmental, health, safety and security performance.\n\u00bf\tTo promote Responsible Care; by encouraging and assisting others to adhere to Responsible Care Principles.\n\nThe general accidental release prevention program and chemical-specific prevention steps:\n\nSynthomer's general accidental release prevention program includes:\n\u00bf\tDesigning for safety including redundant safety systems\n\u00bf\tUse of automatic and manual shutoff valves\n\u00bf\tConducting Process Hazards Analyses (PHAs) studies on production areas\n\u00bf\tManual and automatic fire suppression systems\n\u00bf\tSite-wide preventive maintenance and mechanical integrity programs\n\u00bf\tUse of recommissioning checklists\nChemical-specific measures include:\n\u00bf\tUse of combustible gas analyzers and excess flow valves on the 2-methylpropene storage tank\n\u00bf\tUse of ammonia detectors and excess flow valves on the anhydrous ammonia tank\n\u00bf\tIn-tank automatic foam suppression systems in 1,3-pentadiene storage tanks\n\u00bf\tFusible links which melt in a fire at the hydrogen storage area as well as piping all vents and reliefs to a safe location \n\u00bf      A totally enclosed storage facility equipped with an emergency scrubber for boron trifluoride\n\nThe five-year accident history:\n\nSynthomer has not experienced any RMP accidents within the past five years as of November 21, 2023.\n\nThe emergency response program:\n\nSynthomer maintains an on-site Emergency Response Team which is trained to respond to fires, accidental releases, and confined space entry rescues.  The site also maintains two fire trucks, a confined space rescue vehicle, and a hazardous materials response vehicle which are always available on site.  In addition, the site has entered"
    },
    {
      "ESSeqNum": 2,
      "FacilityID": 1000096682,
      "SummaryText": "into mutual aid agreements with local fire departments in the event that outside resources are needed to respond to an emergency.\n\nPlanned changes to improve safety:\n\nThere are no current planned changes to improve safety systems related to RMP-covered chemicals."
